n democracy. By studying the way these contests unfolded across a startling variety of genres—Broadway shows, radio plays, urban ethnographies, real estate documents, and even children’s programming—Looker shows that the neighborhood ideal has functioned as a central symbolic site for advancing and debating theories about American national identity and democratic practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCities and townszUnited States. 0aNeighborhoods - United States. 0aNeighborhoodszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  acities, urban spaces, community, democracy, political, politics, postwar, 20th century, american, united states of america, usa, history, historical, neighborhood, cultural studies, sociology, broadway shows, radio plays, ethnography, real estate, physical space, identity, towns, privatization, individualism, great society, pluralism, presidential elections, gender, feminism, men and women, class, religion, catholicism, christianity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022607398940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226290454423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226290454/original  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles